UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12331
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The purpose of this paper is to analyze the impact of preferential regulatory treatment on banks' demand for government bonds. Using unique transaction-level data, our analysis suggests that preferential treatment in microprudential liquidity and capital regulation significantly increases banks' demand for government bonds. Liquidity and capital regulation also seem to incentivize banks to substitute other bonds with government bonds. We also find evidence that this ?regulatory effect? leads banks to reduce lending to the real economy.
ER  - 

